suloTaAnN c
suloTaAnN Strength, might, force, or power; (TA;) as also saloTanapN↓: (Bd in iii. 144:) predominance; the possession, or exercise, of superior power or force, or of dominion, or authority, and power, or of absolute dominion or authority and power; (Mgh;) as also suloTapN↓; (S;) the former being syn. with tasalRuTN [used as a subst.]; (Mgh;) and the latter being the subst. from tasalRaTa: (S:) power of dominion; sovereign, or ruling, power; (M;) [in this sense, as well as in the first,] i. q. saloTanapN↓; (Msb;) power of a king; (Lth, Mgh, K;) and of a governor; (Mgh, Msb;) [i. e.] delegated power, or power given to one who is not a king; (TA;) also written suloTaAnN; (M, Msb, K;) which is the only instance of this form: (Msb:) it is masc. and fem.; (M, TA;) generally masc., in the opinion of the skilful; but sometimes fem.; so say IAmb and Zj and others: (Msb:) but ISk says that it is fem. (TA.) One says, (ISk,) or some say, (Msb,) qaDato bihi AlsRuloTaAnu (ISk, Msb) The sovereign, or ruling, power (AlsRaloTanapu↓) decreed it. (Msb.) And Aboo-Zuheyr says, I heard one, in whose chasteness of speech I have confidence, say, OatatonaA suloTaAnN jaAYirapN [A tyrannical sovereign, or ruling, power, came to us]. (Msb.) It is said in a trad., UilRaA Oano tasoOala caA suloTaAnK, meaning Unless thou ask the ruler, or governor, or the king, for thy due from the public treasury. (Mgh.) And you say, qado jaEalotu laka suloTaAnFA EalaI Oaxoci HaqRiI mino fulaAnK I have given thee power, or authority, to take, or receive, my due from such a one. (TA.) And laA yaWumRu AlrRajulu AlrRajula fiI suloTaAnihi [A man shall not take precedence of a man in his authority]; meaning, in his house, and where he has predominance, or superior power, or authority; nor shall he sit upon his cushion; for in doing so he would show him contempt. (Mgh.) ― -b2- Strength, or hardness, of anything: (M, K:) sharpness of anything: force, or violence, of anything. (TA.) The vehemence of winter. (TK.) An excited and predominant state of the blood; or inflammation thereof. (IDrd, M, K.) The flaming, or blazing, of fire. (IDrd.) ― -b3- A proof; an evidence; an argument;
a plea; an allegation; syn. HujRapN, (S, M, Mgh, Msb, K,) and burohaAnN: (S, Msb:) a HujRap being thus called because of the force with which truth attacks the mind: (B:) or, accord. to Mohammad Ibn-Yezeed, from saliyTN, (M, TA,) signifying “ oil of olives, ” because it enlightens: (TA:) and in these senses it has no pl., because it is used in the place of an inf. n. (S, TA.) Accord. to I'Ab, it signifies HujRap wherever it occurs in the Kur. (TA.) But in the words of the Kur [xvii. 35], faqado jaEalonaA liwalRiyihi suloTaAnFA, the meaning may be either [We have given to his executor, or heir,] authority, and power, or absolute authority and power, or the like; or a plea, or the like. (Mgh.) And again, in the Kur [lxix. 29], halaka EanRiI suloTaAniyaho, the meaning may be My dominion, and my authority and power over men, has perished from me; or my plea. (Bd, B.) And sometimes it means A miracle; as in the words of the Kur [li. 38], Uico OarosalonaAhu UilaI firoEawona bisuloTaAn K mubiynK [When we sent him to Pharaoh with a manifest miracle]. (TA.) Az says that it is sometimes masc. because it has a masc. form; and thus it is in the last of the instances above. (TA.) ― -b4- Also A ruler, or governor, or the like; a king; a sovereign; (S, K, TA;) a khaleefeh: (TA:) these are its most common applications [in the writings of post-classical times]: (TA:) thus applied because the person so called is made to predominate; to have, or exercise, superior power or force; to have dominion, or the like: or because he is one of the evidences of God: (Aboo-Bekr, TA:) or because he possesses proof or evidence [of his right]: or because by him pleas and rights are established: (TA:) or because he enlightens the earth, (Msb, * B,) and is of great usefulness; (B;) the word being derived from saliyTN [signifying “ olive-oil ”]: (Msb:) it is of the measure fuEolaAnN: (S:) and when [thus] applied to a person, it is masc.: (Msb:) or it is masc. and fem.: (S, TA:) accord. to Mohammad Ibn-Yezeed, (TA,) fem. because it is [originally] pl. of saliyTN applied to “ oil; ” as though the kingdom shone by him; or because it has the signification of HujRapN: and sometimes masc., because regarded as meaning a man; (K, TA;) or because regarded as a sing.: so says Mohammad Ibn-Yezeed; but Az observes that none beside him says this: Fr says that he who makes it masc. regards it as meaning rajulN; and he who makes it fem. regards it as meaning HujRapN: (TA:) the pl. is salaATiynu. (S, Msb.) It is also, itself, sometimes used as a pl.; as in the phrase sayRidu AlsRuloTaAni, used by a poet, meaning sayRidu AlsRalaATiyna [The lord of kings]; i. e. the khaleefeh: [but this may be rendered the lord of sovereign power, &c.:] or, as some say, the latter word is here pl. of saliyTN, like as rugofaAnN is pl. of ragiyfN. (Msb.)

8 AstnR c
8. AstnR He rubbed and cleaned his teeth with the siwaAk [or piece of stick used for that purpose];
(S, M, L, K;) he made use of the siwaAk, passing it over his teeth. (L.) ― -b2- And He took, or seized, with the teeth. (KL.) ＝ -A2- AstnRt AlEayonu The eye poured forth its tears. (M, L.) ― -b2- AstnR said of the blood of a wound made with a spear or the like, It issued in a gush. (AZ, L.) ― -b3- Said of the saraAb [or mirage], It was, or became, in a state of commotion, went to and fro, or quivered. (M, L, K.) ― -b4- Said of a horse, i. q. qamaSa [app. as meaning He pranced, leaped, sprang, or bounded]: (S, K:) he frisked; or was brisk, lively, or sprightly: he ran, in his friskiness, briskness, liveliness, or sprightliness, in one direction: he ran, by reason of his friskiness, briskness, liveliness, or sprightliness, a heat, or two heats, without a rider upon him: (L:) he ran to and fro, by reason of briskness, liveliness, or sprightliness: from sanRa as signifying “ he poured forth ” water, and as signifying “ he sharpened ” iron upon a whetstone. (Har p. 47.) It is said in a prov., AisotanRati AlfiSaAlu HatRaI AlqaroEaI, (S, Meyd, L,) or AlfuSolaAnu, (Meyd,) i. e. The young weaned camels leaped, sprang, or bounded; (S * L;) even those affected with the small pustules called qaraE; (Meyd, L;) which are small white pustules, the remedy for which is salt, and the butter (jubaAb) of camels' milk: (Meyd:) when the healthy young weaned camels do thus, those affected with such pustules do the like in imitation, but become disabled from doing it by weakness: the prov. is applied to the man who introduces himself among a people, or party, to whom he does not belong: (L:) or to him who speaks with one before whom he should not speak by reason of the greatness of his rank: and some related it differently, saying, AlqurayoEaI [which is the dim. of AlqaroEaI]; (Meyd;) and AlquroEu [which is pl. of AlOaqoraEu, q. v.]: and some say that AstnRt AlfiSaAlu signifies the young weaned camels became fat, or plump, and their skins became [sleek] like masaAnR [or whetstones]. (L.) And it is said in a trad. of 'Omar, raOayotu OabaAhu yasotanRu bisayofihi kamaA yasotanRu Aljamalu, meaning [I saw his father] exulting with briskness, liveliness, or sprightliness, and brandishing his sword, [like as the camel exults with briskness, and lashes with his tail.] (L.) See also 5. ― -b5- [Also He took, held, or followed, the sanan, i. e., road, or way, or main and middle part thereof: and he, or it, was, or lay, in the way. Hence,] one says, xuco maA QsotanRa, meaning [Take thou what lies in the way;] what is easily attainable; what offers itself without difficulty. (AA, TA voce Ainotadaba.) ― -b6- See also 1, near the end of the paragragh, in two places.
